WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.380
Yeah, let's kick this off.

00:00:01.460 --> 00:00:03.900
Okay, so hello everyone.

00:00:03.900 --> 00:00:05.360
I'm Leijie Wang.

00:00:05.460 --> 00:00:08.520
I'm a PhD student from University of Washington.

00:00:08.520 --> 00:00:11.550
Even though I'm at Seattle, very close to Vancouver,

00:00:11.560 --> 00:00:14.120
but because of the visa issues, I cannot come in person

00:00:14.240 --> 00:00:14.460
.

00:00:14.460 --> 00:00:15.760
So that's why I'm over the Zoom.

00:00:15.760 --> 00:00:19.440
But today I would like to be glad to present our work

00:00:19.440 --> 00:00:22.980
about Blue Sky Custom Feeds and the title, Understand the

00:00:22.980 --> 00:00:24.960
Landscape of Custom Feeds on Blue Sky.

00:00:24.960 --> 00:00:29.640
I'll start with thinking about the platforms you use every day

00:00:29.640 --> 00:00:29.960
.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:32.550
Like YouTube, TikTok, Instagram, or Spotify.

00:00:32.560 --> 00:00:36.330
Each of them has a recommendation feed that feels quite personal to

00:00:36.330 --> 00:00:36.780
you.

00:00:36.780 --> 00:00:40.600
But you have no saying how that particular algorithm works or what

00:00:40.600 --> 00:00:41.790
you're optimized for.

00:00:41.860 --> 00:00:44.410
Like whether you're optimized for likes or dislikes.

00:00:44.420 --> 00:00:49.070
The ranking is just instead decided by those single centralized algorithms controlled

00:00:49.070 --> 00:00:50.260
by those big companies.

00:00:50.260 --> 00:00:55.080
And this concentration of power in these days has two consequences.

00:00:55.080 --> 00:00:58.820
So first, you don't have no visibility into why certain

00:00:58.820 --> 00:01:00.380
content appeal into their feed.

00:01:00.400 --> 00:01:02.280
The algorithm is just a black box.

00:01:02.280 --> 00:01:05.930
And we see a lot of complaints about them in these days

00:01:05.930 --> 00:01:06.240
.

00:01:06.240 --> 00:01:10.430
And the second, creators often learn to optimize for that particular

00:01:10.430 --> 00:01:11.990
algorithm to appease them.

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:14.920
And over time, we can see the content start to become

00:01:14.920 --> 00:01:16.550
homogeneous everywhere.

00:01:16.600 --> 00:01:18.980
Like there are all kinds of clickbait kind of content.

00:01:20.320 --> 00:01:22.760
And this is what Blue Sky does something different here.

00:01:22.760 --> 00:01:24.620
Like they call algorithmic choice.

00:01:24.620 --> 00:01:27.940
Blue Sky Custom Feeds allow users to create, subscribe,

00:01:27.940 --> 00:01:32.620
and share their feed algorithms instead of being stuck with that particular

00:01:32.620 --> 00:01:33.280
default.

00:01:33.940 --> 00:01:36.660
And on the consumer side, the field consumers, they can

00:01:36.660 --> 00:01:40.060
further subscribe to the feeds offered by their communities.

00:01:40.060 --> 00:01:43.500
And on the creator side, third-party tools make it

00:01:43.500 --> 00:01:47.100
possible for anyone to build and publish their own feeds.

00:01:49.100 --> 00:01:51.940
This connects to a very long-standing vision in the research

00:01:51.940 --> 00:01:54.500
community, the idea of middleware.

00:01:54.500 --> 00:01:56.490
The core idea is simple.

00:01:56.500 --> 00:02:00.480
What if the social media services, like recommendation, moderation,

00:02:00.480 --> 00:02:03.530
or the governance in the communities, did not have to be

00:02:03.530 --> 00:02:05.640
controlled by the platforms?

00:02:06.480 --> 00:02:10.360
What if they could be provided by these independent middleware services

00:02:10.360 --> 00:02:13.100
so that users have the choice among them?

00:02:13.140 --> 00:02:18.800
And this is just a theoretical vision is already happening at scale

00:02:19.020 --> 00:02:19.180
.

00:02:19.180 --> 00:02:21.740
Today, as people already know in the room, like the

00:02:21.860 --> 00:02:25.900
Blue Sky today has 42 million active users and over 40,

00:02:25.900 --> 00:02:28.780
000 custom feeds have been created.

00:02:28.780 --> 00:02:32.750
So this makes custom feeds as the first large-scale instant

00:02:32.770 --> 00:02:36.990
iation of the middleware vision for feed recommendation specifically.

00:02:37.020 --> 00:02:42.460
But for this particular ecosystem to work, someone has to actually

00:02:42.460 --> 00:02:43.440
build in their feeds.

00:02:43.440 --> 00:02:46.720
And that's the feed creators we focus in this particular work

00:02:46.760 --> 00:02:47.000
.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:49.280
But we know little about them.

00:02:49.280 --> 00:02:52.100
Like, what motivates them to create feeds in the first place

00:02:52.100 --> 00:02:52.310
?

00:02:52.320 --> 00:02:55.600
And what does it actually take to run a particular custom feed

00:02:55.640 --> 00:02:55.880
?

00:02:55.880 --> 00:02:59.140
And what challenges and opportunities do they face?

00:02:59.140 --> 00:03:01.690
These are the questions driving our work.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:06.370
So in particular, we organize our work around these three research

00:03:06.370 --> 00:03:07.140
questions.

00:03:07.140 --> 00:03:10.420
First, what kinds of custom feeds are there?

00:03:10.460 --> 00:03:15.080
Second, what kinds of how do the feed creators building,

00:03:15.080 --> 00:03:18.280
maintaining, and sustaining their custom feed ecosystem?

00:03:18.280 --> 00:03:23.480
Third, what kinds of challenges and opportunities exist for the custom

00:03:23.480 --> 00:03:24.900
feed ecosystem?

00:03:24.940 --> 00:03:30.200
To answer these research questions, we conducted semi-structured

00:03:30.200 --> 00:03:34.000
interviews with 24 feed creators on Blue Sky.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:37.430
And this particular chart shows the range of feeds they created,

00:03:37.430 --> 00:03:40.200
measured by the likes they received on Blue Sky.

00:03:40.200 --> 00:03:44.270
Some creators that are relatively small, with under like 100 likes

00:03:44.270 --> 00:03:44.500
.

00:03:44.500 --> 00:03:47.870
But there are others who are building feeds over 10,000

00:03:47.870 --> 00:03:48.400
likes.

00:03:48.400 --> 00:03:51.240
So we have a good spread in our interviews, from the

00:03:51.240 --> 00:03:54.100
hobbyist builders to some of the most popular feeds on the

00:03:54.300 --> 00:03:55.010
platform.

00:03:56.680 --> 00:03:58.400
And here we talk about our findings.

00:03:58.400 --> 00:04:03.200
Our first key finding is that we identify there are two kinds

00:04:03.200 --> 00:04:07.300
of feed orientations that the custom feeds can fall into.

00:04:07.320 --> 00:04:10.280
The first is the utility-providing feed.

00:04:10.280 --> 00:04:13.620
They are focused on delivering the content to the feed consumers,

00:04:13.620 --> 00:04:17.090
thinking of them as a well-curated feeder, filter

00:04:17.090 --> 00:04:17.360
.

00:04:18.200 --> 00:04:21.120
And there's also community-building feeds that are very different

00:04:21.120 --> 00:04:21.340
.

00:04:21.340 --> 00:04:24.910
They're cultivating the space for the feed consumers to connect

00:04:24.910 --> 00:04:26.020
with each other.

00:04:26.020 --> 00:04:29.120
And as we will see, these two orientations shape their

00:04:29.120 --> 00:04:33.040
motivations, their daily tasks, and how they're sustaining their

00:04:33.040 --> 00:04:34.220
feeds in the long term.

00:04:34.220 --> 00:04:39.170
Specific for the utility-providing feeds, the feed

00:04:39.170 --> 00:04:42.980
is primarily a content delivery mechanism for the feed consumers.

00:04:42.980 --> 00:04:46.040
The creator's job is mostly done as setup.

00:04:46.680 --> 00:04:50.370
They configure the hashtags, keywords, or data accounts, and

00:04:50.370 --> 00:04:52.660
just let the feed run on the blue sky.

00:04:52.660 --> 00:04:56.440
On the other hand, the feed consumers, they are purely

00:04:56.440 --> 00:04:58.220
receptive or passive.

00:04:58.220 --> 00:05:01.360
They just follow the feed like they're following a particular channel

00:05:01.360 --> 00:05:03.060
or follow a particular blog site.

00:05:03.060 --> 00:05:08.330
They do not actively contribute to what particular content appears in the

00:05:08.330 --> 00:05:10.010
feed by themselves.

00:05:10.020 --> 00:05:14.820
And within the utility feed, we also see two distinct sub

00:05:14.820 --> 00:05:15.660
types.

00:05:16.340 --> 00:05:18.900
The first is what we call set it and forget it mode

00:05:19.020 --> 00:05:19.260
.

00:05:19.260 --> 00:05:22.710
People just catch the relevant post of a given topic just with

00:05:22.710 --> 00:05:26.290
a very simple list of keywords, such as mushrooms or some

00:05:26.290 --> 00:05:27.680
fan communities.

00:05:27.680 --> 00:05:31.640
The creator just sets it up once and just largely forgot it

00:05:31.640 --> 00:05:32.860
and step away.

00:05:34.260 --> 00:05:37.430
The second type is very highly curated feeds, those use v

00:05:37.430 --> 00:05:42.180
etted poster lists or custom ranking algorithms to ensure the content they

00:05:42.180 --> 00:05:44.280
delivered are super high quality.

00:05:44.280 --> 00:05:47.020
It's almost like an editor's choice or editor's pick

00:05:47.020 --> 00:05:48.240
in the newspapers.

00:05:48.240 --> 00:05:52.240
Unlike the first type, they require very ongoing maintenance.

00:05:52.280 --> 00:05:57.450
The creators constantly turning and tuning and updating their algorithms to ensure

00:05:57.450 --> 00:05:59.880
the content is always high quality.

00:05:59.880 --> 00:06:04.940
Community building feeds work very differently from these utility feeds.

00:06:04.940 --> 00:06:08.580
Here, the feed consumers are not just passive recipients.

00:06:08.960 --> 00:06:13.170
They actively contribute in the content and interact with each other simply

00:06:13.170 --> 00:06:16.190
by the feed, like they were adding a particular keyword to

00:06:16.190 --> 00:06:20.310
their post so that they're essentially having conversations with each other

00:06:20.380 --> 00:06:21.140
in the feed.

00:06:21.680 --> 00:06:24.920
The feed becomes a very shared social place, and the feed

00:06:24.920 --> 00:06:26.980
creator's role shifts here too.

00:06:26.980 --> 00:06:30.480
Instead of configuring rules, they tend to be social space

00:06:30.480 --> 00:06:34.000
, maintaining norms and keeping the community healthy.

00:06:35.680 --> 00:06:39.080
I will give you two concrete examples of community building feeds.

00:06:39.080 --> 00:06:41.500
So there's a particular feed that we found out in our

00:06:41.500 --> 00:06:42.320
interviews.

00:06:42.320 --> 00:06:46.120
They just surface a post from the users below a particular threshold

00:06:46.120 --> 00:06:49.640
of follower numbers so that they can design it to welcome the

00:06:49.650 --> 00:06:53.340
newcomers and give the less known voices a chance to be

00:06:53.340 --> 00:06:54.900
seen in their feed.

00:06:54.900 --> 00:06:58.290
And another, just like the feed consumers curating the content

00:06:58.290 --> 00:06:59.300
by themselves.

00:06:59.300 --> 00:07:01.860
So they can just reply to any post on Blue Sky with

00:07:01.980 --> 00:07:03.420
a particular keyword.

00:07:03.620 --> 00:07:06.060
And in this way, they are nominating the post to

00:07:06.060 --> 00:07:08.060
appear in the feed automatically.

00:07:08.060 --> 00:07:12.470
And one of our participants captured the creator's role very well

00:07:12.470 --> 00:07:12.760
.

00:07:12.760 --> 00:07:16.040
They said, I almost see myself as a librarian.

00:07:16.060 --> 00:07:18.240
I'm making sure people are not yelling.

00:07:18.240 --> 00:07:21.140
They are not picking up their trash and putting books back when

00:07:21.140 --> 00:07:22.460
they are supposed to be.

00:07:22.460 --> 00:07:26.430
I'm making a place as presentable and welcoming as possible

00:07:26.510 --> 00:07:26.820
.

00:07:26.920 --> 00:07:30.090
So they are just tending to that particular social space as

00:07:30.090 --> 00:07:33.440
a feed creator, which is very different from the utility feed

00:07:33.440 --> 00:07:34.220
creators.

00:07:34.220 --> 00:07:37.390
And after that, let's take a look at how people

00:07:37.390 --> 00:07:39.880
are building their custom feeds.

00:07:39.940 --> 00:07:43.720
And we found out that most feed creators navigate an ecosystem of

00:07:43.720 --> 00:07:45.060
third-party tools.

00:07:45.060 --> 00:07:47.120
They do not have to start from scratch.

00:07:47.560 --> 00:07:50.020
But for some of them, those tools are not enough for

00:07:50.020 --> 00:07:50.840
their needs.

00:07:50.840 --> 00:07:53.160
So they end up building their own infrastructures.

00:07:54.700 --> 00:07:57.620
So for example, most feed creators, they rely on third

00:07:57.620 --> 00:07:58.560
-party tools.

00:07:58.560 --> 00:08:01.480
And there is a real diversity of options for them.

00:08:01.480 --> 00:08:04.960
Brown Sky Feed, Blue Sky Feed creators, and Grace,

00:08:04.960 --> 00:08:06.420
just to name a few.

00:08:07.060 --> 00:08:10.450
So the variety matters, it means that the creators can always

00:08:10.450 --> 00:08:14.400
choose a tool that best fits their needs and their technical levels

00:08:14.410 --> 00:08:14.660
.

00:08:14.660 --> 00:08:19.460
Within these tools, creators try to combine various kinds of building

00:08:19.460 --> 00:08:22.440
blocks to shape what appears in the feed.

00:08:22.440 --> 00:08:27.060
Some using those keywords or regular expression matching to catch a post

00:08:27.060 --> 00:08:28.560
on a specific topic.

00:08:28.560 --> 00:08:32.200
Others try to maintain the vetted accounts list, hand-

00:08:32.200 --> 00:08:35.060
picking who got included in their feed.

00:08:35.800 --> 00:08:38.390
And some also use a Blue Sky Labellers system to

00:08:38.480 --> 00:08:42.440
help filter the content as part of their content moderation efforts.

00:08:42.460 --> 00:08:46.720
But the third-party do not work for everyone.

00:08:46.720 --> 00:08:50.520
Some creators have the needs that go beyond what existing tools can

00:08:50.520 --> 00:08:51.270
support.

00:08:51.300 --> 00:08:53.790
And they end up building their own infrastructures.

00:08:53.800 --> 00:08:58.870
So for instance, one participant built a fully personalized recommendation system

00:08:58.870 --> 00:08:59.640
on their own.

00:08:59.640 --> 00:09:03.080
Because they need a fine-grained interaction data that this

00:09:03.080 --> 00:09:05.620
third-party tool simply cannot access.

00:09:05.800 --> 00:09:10.860
And another tried to run a custom implementation in Rust because their

00:09:10.860 --> 00:09:14.710
feed lodges are often too complex for any block-based

00:09:14.750 --> 00:09:17.340
tools offered by these third-party tools.

00:09:17.340 --> 00:09:20.150
And they also need to support a much larger scale of use

00:09:20.150 --> 00:09:20.390
.

00:09:20.400 --> 00:09:23.870
So in this way, these feed creators are not casual hobby

00:09:23.870 --> 00:09:25.800
ists who just try it for fun.

00:09:25.800 --> 00:09:30.480
They are essentially running some independent technical infrastructure through the custom feeds

00:09:30.480 --> 00:09:30.720
.

00:09:30.720 --> 00:09:36.340
And our third key finding is about what it takes to maintain

00:09:36.340 --> 00:09:38.980
a custom feed over time.

00:09:39.580 --> 00:09:42.380
And it turns out the maintenance goes well beyond just keeping the

00:09:42.380 --> 00:09:43.580
hour with them running.

00:09:43.600 --> 00:09:47.770
Creators are handling moderation, deriving discovery, and try

00:09:47.770 --> 00:09:50.220
to listen to the consumer feedback.

00:09:50.260 --> 00:09:53.660
And for most of these tasks, they get very little support

00:09:53.660 --> 00:09:55.520
from the Blue Sky platform.

00:09:57.580 --> 00:10:02.110
So for instance, the utility providing feed, the moderation effort

00:10:02.110 --> 00:10:06.030
is very different across these different kinds of feeds.

00:10:06.040 --> 00:10:09.490
But for the utility providing feeds, it's more about largely

00:10:09.490 --> 00:10:10.590
upfront effort.

00:10:10.620 --> 00:10:14.250
They set up some strict rules to deliver the content, which

00:10:14.250 --> 00:10:18.160
means that usually there isn't much toxic content to moderate for

00:10:18.160 --> 00:10:20.060
after the feed goes alive.

00:10:20.440 --> 00:10:23.580
But for the community feed, it's often ongoing because the

00:10:23.580 --> 00:10:25.840
community itself is always evolving.

00:10:25.840 --> 00:10:28.940
There's new member joins, there's new dynamic emerge,

00:10:28.940 --> 00:10:31.440
and norms need to be actively maintained.

00:10:31.440 --> 00:10:34.170
And on top of that, the moderation deletion is

00:10:34.170 --> 00:10:35.760
also much more nuanced.

00:10:35.760 --> 00:10:38.610
It's not just about the topic being misaligned with

00:10:38.610 --> 00:10:41.400
your feed topic, but instead it's a social delet

00:10:41.400 --> 00:10:41.840
ion.

00:10:41.840 --> 00:10:44.430
They need to carefully make sure their deletions do not

00:10:44.520 --> 00:10:46.340
hurt the community relationship.

00:10:48.440 --> 00:10:51.720
And the Blue Sky also decentralizes the creation of the feed

00:10:51.760 --> 00:10:54.850
, but they do not decentralize the discovery of the feed

00:10:54.850 --> 00:10:55.060
.

00:10:55.140 --> 00:10:58.840
The feed tab on the Blue Sky is often static, ranked

00:10:58.840 --> 00:11:02.220
by the popularities, serving the same set of feeds that

00:11:02.270 --> 00:11:03.810
were popular two years ago.

00:11:03.820 --> 00:11:06.730
And for the new feeds, especially non-engaged ones

00:11:06.730 --> 00:11:09.510
, they have little chance to be seen by the newcomers

00:11:09.720 --> 00:11:09.940
.

00:11:09.940 --> 00:11:13.480
And the creators need to take matters into their own time.

00:11:13.700 --> 00:11:16.580
They have to promote the feeds by themselves, on the social

00:11:16.580 --> 00:11:19.160
media, in the communities, whenever they can.

00:11:20.540 --> 00:11:23.700
And we heard these frustrations directed from the creators.

00:11:23.700 --> 00:11:28.560
One participant told us, I have been commenting on every single

00:11:28.630 --> 00:11:31.600
feed topic post I found, telling them about the feeds and

00:11:31.600 --> 00:11:33.580
how to set up their Blue Sky accounts.

00:11:33.620 --> 00:11:37.000
And they've sent out thousands of messages.

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:41.100
And they concluded that, even though the feed is successful,

00:11:41.100 --> 00:11:44.200
but obviously it's not a sustainable strategy for a lot of

00:11:44.200 --> 00:11:45.280
feed creators.

00:11:45.280 --> 00:11:50.060
And another participant complained that, if creating a new account and

00:11:50.060 --> 00:11:52.500
they go to the feed tab, you will see the same

00:11:52.500 --> 00:11:54.240
top feed from two years ago.

00:11:54.240 --> 00:11:57.610
They are all in English and often only about the United States

00:11:57.610 --> 00:11:57.860
.

00:11:57.860 --> 00:12:00.740
So it's not interesting for the people outside of the United

00:12:00.740 --> 00:12:01.360
States.

00:12:03.620 --> 00:12:08.060
And the centralized algorithms can improve the continuously on these YouTube or

00:12:08.060 --> 00:12:09.280
TikTok platforms.

00:12:09.320 --> 00:12:11.840
They're listening to your clicks, your skips, and

00:12:11.840 --> 00:12:15.500
the dwell times, and feedback into their recommendation algorithms.

00:12:15.500 --> 00:12:18.090
But in the Blue Sky for the custom feeds, they have

00:12:18.180 --> 00:12:20.050
not that kind of infrastructure.

00:12:21.120 --> 00:12:24.640
There are several kinds of feedback they can tap into, like

00:12:24.640 --> 00:12:27.870
they get some implicit feedbacks from the people who likes,

00:12:27.870 --> 00:12:31.020
replies, or reposts their feeds from their custom feeds

00:12:31.040 --> 00:12:31.260
.

00:12:31.260 --> 00:12:35.640
But they lack the technical tools to actually analyze and learn from

00:12:35.640 --> 00:12:36.950
this data at scale.

00:12:37.080 --> 00:12:40.630
They also got a lot of some sort of explicit feedback from

00:12:40.630 --> 00:12:45.580
their direct messages or some survey responses they distributed in their feed

00:12:45.660 --> 00:12:46.040
.

00:12:46.120 --> 00:12:49.080
But it's often very rare and only come from the people

00:12:49.080 --> 00:12:52.480
who are mostly motivated to consume their feed content.

00:12:52.480 --> 00:12:56.120
There are also some third-party tools that provide some basic

00:12:56.120 --> 00:13:00.150
analytics, things like the daily active users or the posted volumes

00:13:00.150 --> 00:13:00.440
.

00:13:00.440 --> 00:13:03.890
But this only tells the feed creators that the feed is still

00:13:03.900 --> 00:13:07.440
alive, but not whether it's actually working on that.

00:13:07.440 --> 00:13:10.250
The result is that the feed creators do not get a lot

00:13:10.250 --> 00:13:13.420
of feedback to continuously improving their feed.

00:13:13.560 --> 00:13:16.130
And in the long term, they just lose their motivation to

00:13:16.240 --> 00:13:16.660
do that.

00:13:16.660 --> 00:13:22.320
And our fourth and final key finding is about sustaining the custom

00:13:22.560 --> 00:13:23.280
feeds.

00:13:23.340 --> 00:13:27.460
The custom feed ecosystem, over 40,000 feeds, run

00:13:27.460 --> 00:13:30.070
almost entirely on volunteer labels.

00:13:30.080 --> 00:13:33.600
Creators need to adopt the cost of running the feed themselves

00:13:33.600 --> 00:13:36.340
, with very little to no platform support.

00:13:37.120 --> 00:13:40.390
And what is sustaining them isn't their financial incentives or the

00:13:40.390 --> 00:13:41.800
platform recognitions.

00:13:41.800 --> 00:13:44.290
It's often just intrinsic motivation.

00:13:44.300 --> 00:13:48.470
And if we take a step back, there's some cost

00:13:48.470 --> 00:13:50.840
of sustaining a feed.

00:13:50.840 --> 00:13:53.780
And on the infrastructure side, the creators need to pay out

00:13:53.780 --> 00:13:57.320
of the pocket for third-party tool subscriptions to keep their

00:13:57.320 --> 00:13:58.320
feed running.

00:13:58.400 --> 00:14:01.500
And beyond the money, there's also time commitment.

00:14:01.500 --> 00:14:04.780
They have to do the regular maintenance, moderation, and responding

00:14:04.820 --> 00:14:05.980
to the user feedback.

00:14:05.980 --> 00:14:09.450
But what keeps the creator going, we call it the hobby

00:14:09.450 --> 00:14:10.360
ist model.

00:14:10.360 --> 00:14:12.420
The motivation is the owning few.

00:14:12.440 --> 00:14:17.520
For the utility-providing creators, seeing their subscriber account

00:14:17.520 --> 00:14:18.940
grow is a key signal.

00:14:19.260 --> 00:14:22.520
It tells them the feed is still useful and worth maintaining.

00:14:22.520 --> 00:14:26.160
But that also is saying that without that particular signal, feed

00:14:26.160 --> 00:14:28.900
creators are more likely to lose motivations.

00:14:28.900 --> 00:14:32.590
And that's why we have this bunch of set and forget

00:14:32.590 --> 00:14:35.120
it feeds for the utility part.

00:14:35.120 --> 00:14:39.310
For the community-building creators, the motivation comes from something

00:14:39.310 --> 00:14:40.420
very different.

00:14:40.420 --> 00:14:43.380
They are seeing that people are actually connecting with each other through

00:14:43.380 --> 00:14:44.020
their feed.

00:14:44.020 --> 00:14:46.420
And that makes them happy about their job.

00:14:46.620 --> 00:14:50.590
But this mirrors what we see in those volunteer ecosystems like Reddit

00:14:50.590 --> 00:14:53.940
and Discord, where the community itself is just a reward.

00:14:53.940 --> 00:14:58.490
We also asked about feed creators about monetarization, and

00:14:58.540 --> 00:15:02.240
most felt that not all the feeds can justify it.

00:15:02.240 --> 00:15:05.850
The key factor is that whether the feed is built on dedicated

00:15:05.850 --> 00:15:07.660
, irreplaceable effort.

00:15:07.660 --> 00:15:10.600
So, for example, the set and forget feeds, they

00:15:10.600 --> 00:15:12.400
are very easy to replicate.

00:15:12.720 --> 00:15:15.650
If someone charges for it, users can just build the feeds

00:15:15.650 --> 00:15:17.340
by themselves, elsewhere.

00:15:17.340 --> 00:15:21.680
But for the highly curated feeds, they are very different.

00:15:21.680 --> 00:15:25.130
The creators have the ongoing effort and judgment to make the feed

00:15:25.130 --> 00:15:27.140
valuable to their feed consumers.

00:15:27.140 --> 00:15:30.750
And we do see some successful examples of monetarization in

00:15:30.750 --> 00:15:32.780
that space in our interviews.

00:15:35.340 --> 00:15:38.790
Creators volunteer their efforts very willingly, but they also think

00:15:38.790 --> 00:15:41.880
the infrastructure costs deserve some financial support.

00:15:41.880 --> 00:15:46.680
One participant put it very simply that it's not about getting

00:15:46.680 --> 00:15:47.380
rich.

00:15:47.380 --> 00:15:49.520
It's just about getting covering expense.

00:15:49.520 --> 00:15:51.780
So I'm not going to pay out of the pocket to

00:15:51.780 --> 00:15:53.200
help the community.

00:15:54.260 --> 00:15:57.470
And another friend, even more positive, they're charging a

00:15:57.470 --> 00:16:00.600
small amount of dollars isn't just fair to the creators.

00:16:00.600 --> 00:16:04.570
It's creating a positive loop of dollars going through the communities

00:16:04.650 --> 00:16:08.720
so that the whole Blue Sky Custom Feeds can go more

00:16:08.720 --> 00:16:09.510
alive.

00:16:09.540 --> 00:16:13.840
So with all these findings, we have these two design implications

00:16:13.840 --> 00:16:17.290
to see how we can further improve the Blue Sky Custom Fe

00:16:17.290 --> 00:16:20.060
eds as a community, and also as researchers.

00:16:20.060 --> 00:16:24.250
We see there's two key directions to better support feed creators

00:16:24.250 --> 00:16:26.920
beyond the initial building process.

00:16:26.920 --> 00:16:30.140
First, we need to help creators to better make sense of

00:16:30.140 --> 00:16:33.650
the implicit feedback they get from their feed creators.

00:16:33.660 --> 00:16:37.580
Feed consumers like likes, reports, and replies exist.

00:16:37.580 --> 00:16:41.310
But creators need to better choose to better turn into that noisy

00:16:41.310 --> 00:16:45.010
data, into some actionable insights they can use to improve their

00:16:45.010 --> 00:16:45.600
feeds.

00:16:47.360 --> 00:16:50.200
Second, we also need to rethink about the feed discovery.

00:16:50.200 --> 00:16:53.050
Right now, it's still platform-controlled, even though

00:16:53.050 --> 00:16:55.580
it's very fair-controlled, like it's always ranked

00:16:55.600 --> 00:16:56.800
by the popularities.

00:16:56.800 --> 00:17:01.080
But enabling more personalized feed discovery, beyond just the platform-

00:17:01.080 --> 00:17:04.800
controlled ranking, will give new users, and not English feeds

00:17:04.800 --> 00:17:07.970
, a real chance to reach to the right users.

00:17:08.100 --> 00:17:13.580
And we also want to say something about the sustainability.

00:17:14.360 --> 00:17:17.920
If creators burn out and cannot cover their costs, feeds just

00:17:17.920 --> 00:17:22.610
will stop being maintained, and the communities building around them will

00:17:22.610 --> 00:17:23.680
slowly go away.

00:17:23.680 --> 00:17:28.020
From our interviews, we've found two potential positives that the

00:17:28.020 --> 00:17:31.520
feed creators themselves are already experienced with.

00:17:31.520 --> 00:17:33.360
One is their donations.

00:17:33.360 --> 00:17:36.410
They will solicit some donations from their feed consumers.

00:17:37.060 --> 00:17:40.680
This is similar to how the Wikipedia sustain itself through those volunteer

00:17:40.680 --> 00:17:42.220
-like community donations.

00:17:42.220 --> 00:17:47.020
And we also see those popular feeds doing transparent advertising.

00:17:47.020 --> 00:17:50.400
They have some ads within their feeds, but the ad is

00:17:50.400 --> 00:17:52.900
opt-in, and the community scoped ads, so

00:17:53.060 --> 00:17:55.780
that they can keep the revenue, but do not deliver like

00:17:55.780 --> 00:17:58.220
very irrelevant ads to their consumers.

00:17:59.340 --> 00:18:02.830
Although, neither of them is a perfect solution, but they

00:18:02.830 --> 00:18:06.070
both point out towards a model where the community of the custom

00:18:06.120 --> 00:18:10.020
feeds can support the infrastructure and support itself in the long term

00:18:10.020 --> 00:18:10.260
.

00:18:10.260 --> 00:18:15.580
Here's all of our presentations, and thank you for everyone

00:18:15.580 --> 00:18:17.500
listening, even though it's over Zoom.

00:18:17.500 --> 00:18:19.300
And do you have any questions?

00:18:19.300 --> 00:18:20.760
And here's my contact.

00:18:20.840 --> 00:18:29.940
Do we have any questions, comments, thoughts

00:18:29.940 --> 00:18:30.680
?

00:18:30.680 --> 00:18:33.310
Nope?

00:18:33.360 --> 00:18:35.240
Oh, what you got?

00:18:35.240 --> 00:18:39.160
If you were managing Blue Sky, the app, what would

00:18:39.160 --> 00:18:39.960
you do?

00:18:39.960 --> 00:18:42.790
The question was, if you were managing Blue Sky, the

00:18:42.790 --> 00:18:44.280
app, what would you do?

00:18:45.620 --> 00:18:48.500
I think, as I can see in the design implications,

00:18:48.500 --> 00:18:51.560
I would at least try to improve the feed discovery feature.

00:18:51.560 --> 00:18:54.100
Like, I think people do want that part to be,

00:18:54.100 --> 00:18:57.050
like, it's inevitable they're going to be some sort

00:18:57.050 --> 00:19:00.950
of centralized by the Blue Sky platform to design how to rank

00:19:00.950 --> 00:19:03.720
in these different kinds of feeds.

00:19:03.720 --> 00:19:06.310
But obviously, I think one single feature you can see just

00:19:06.400 --> 00:19:09.300
to recommend relevant feeds for people to explore, so that they

00:19:09.340 --> 00:19:12.760
're not being stuck in those popularity ranking feeds, which is

00:19:12.760 --> 00:19:15.410
always just the same set of feeds all over the years.

00:19:16.080 --> 00:19:19.970
And I think another important part people constantly want is about better

00:19:19.970 --> 00:19:22.960
guidelines, about how to do the advertisement in their feeds.

00:19:23.040 --> 00:19:25.440
Like, people are kind of trying to figure it out by

00:19:25.440 --> 00:19:29.130
themselves and trying to testing that in their own population, the

00:19:29.130 --> 00:19:30.690
consumer's populations.

00:19:30.740 --> 00:19:33.840
But it's more beneficial for them to see, like,

00:19:33.840 --> 00:19:37.060
what kinds of ads are tolerable in the feeds so that

00:19:37.060 --> 00:19:40.790
they can be more actionable and more comfortable to place ads in

00:19:40.790 --> 00:19:43.280
their feeds so that they're not going to do the free

00:19:43.280 --> 00:19:44.860
label for the whole ecosystem.

00:19:45.620 --> 00:19:52.080
I think that's it.

00:19:52.080 --> 00:19:52.860
Thank you very much.

00:19:52.860 --> 00:19:53.280
Yeah.

00:19:53.280 --> 00:19:54.550
Thank you, everyone.

00:19:54.560 --> 00:19:55.040
Cheers.
